<div class="content">
  <h2>Glass vs Plastic vs Silicone Storage</h2>
  <p>Glass storage containers like Pyrex, OXO, and Glasslock are excellent because they do not stain or absorb odors, and they are safe for the microwave, oven, and dishwasher. However, they are heavy and breakable. BPA-free plastic containers, such as Rubbermaid Brilliance or Snapware, are lightweight, durable, and great for taking lunch on the go, but they can stain or warp over time. Silicone storage, like Stasher bags, is highly versatile, able to go from freezer to boiling water to microwave seamlessly while taking up minimal space.</p>

  <h2>Meal Prep Container Guide</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Portion Control:</strong> Look for containers with dividers if you want to keep different foods separated.</li>
    <li><strong>Leak-proof Seals:</strong> Crucial if you are carrying soups or stews. OXO Good Grips and Rubbermaid Brilliance are excellent choices.</li>
    <li><strong>Stackability:</strong> Vital for saving fridge and freezer space. Most matching sets nest neatly.</li>
    <li><strong>Freezer-safe:</strong> Ensure the container won't become brittle and crack when frozen. Both high-quality glass and specific plastics are freezer safe.</li>
    <li><strong>Microwave-safe:</strong> Important for easy reheating. Always vent the lid or remove it completely before microwaving to avoid pressure buildup.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Organization Tips</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Declutter First:</strong> Discard or recycle any containers with missing lids, severe stains, or cracks.</li>
    <li><strong>Stick to One Brand:</strong> This is the easiest way to ensure lids and bases are interchangeable and nest efficiently.</li>
    <li><strong>Lid Storage:</strong> Store lids vertically using a dedicated organizer, a dish drying rack, or a large bin to keep them from avalanching.</li>
    <li><strong>Nesting Bases:</strong> Stack bases inside each other, separated by shape (rectangles together, circles together).</li>
    <li><strong>Zone Your Cabinets:</strong> Dedicate a specific drawer or shelf solely to food storage containers to prevent them from taking over the kitchen.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Are glass food storage containers better than plastic?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Glass containers are generally better because they are more durable, won't stain or retain odors, and are safer for microwave and oven use. However, plastic containers are lighter and won't shatter if dropped.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the best way to organize food storage containers?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">The best way to organize containers is to buy matching sets that stack easily. Keep lids and bottoms together, or store lids vertically in a dedicated organizer rack. Declutter unmatched pieces regularly.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I put hot food in plastic storage containers?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">It is not recommended to put boiling hot food directly into plastic containers. Let the food cool down slightly first to prevent warping or potential leaching of chemicals, even in BPA-free plastics.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Are silicone bags like Stasher microwave safe?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes, high-quality silicone bags like Stasher are microwave safe. They can also be used in the dishwasher, freezer, and even in boiling water for sous-vide cooking. Leave the bag partially open when microwaving to vent steam.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
